  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Here's a breakdown of some key ones:\n\n**Key International Conventions and Organizations:**\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** While not a law itself, FATF is a crucial inter-governmental body. It sets international standards and promotes the effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. FATF recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This is one of the earliest international agreements targeting money laundering. It requires parties to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):** This convention extends the fight against money laundering beyond drug-related offenses to cover a broader range of transnational crimes. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds of crime and to adopt measures for the confiscation of such proceeds.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention Against Corruption (2003):** This convention addresses corruption-related money laundering, requiring countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds of corruption.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990):** This is a regional convention that provides a framework for international cooperation in combating money laundering in Europe.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime and on the Financing of Terrorism (2005):**  An updated version of the 1990 convention, it expands the scope to include the financing of terrorism.\n\n**Key Principles and Obligations Imposed by International Law (as reflected in the conventions and FATF recommendations):**\n\n*   **Criminalization of Money Laundering:**  Countries are obligated to criminalize money laundering based on the proceeds of a wide range of predicate offenses (the underlying crimes that generate the illicit funds).\n*   **Customer Due Diligence (CDD):** Financial institutions are required to identify and verify the identity of their customers (KYC - Know Your Customer).\n*   **Record Keeping:**  Financial institutions must keep records of transactions for a certain period to assist in investigations.\n*   **Reporting of Suspicious Transactions (STR):**  Financial institutions are required to report suspicious transactions to the relevant authorities (Financial Intelligence Units - FIUs).\n*   **International Cooperation:**  Countries are expected to cooperate with each other in investigations and prosecutions of money laundering offenses, including providing mutual legal assistance and extraditing offenders.\n*   **Confiscation and Seizure:** Countries are obligated to establish mechanisms for the confiscation and seizure of assets derived from crime.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Sovereignty:** While international laws set standards, each country is responsible for enacting and enforcing its own domestic laws against money laundering. The degree to which countries comply with international standards can vary.\n*   **Complexity:** Money laundering schemes are often complex and involve multiple jurisdictions, making investigations and prosecutions challenging.\n*   **Evolving Threats:** Money laundering techniques are constantly evolving, requiring ongoing efforts to update and strengthen anti-money laundering measures.\n\n**In summary, there is a robust framework of international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. These instruments impose obligations on countries to criminalize money laundering, implement preventive measures in the financial sector, and cooperate internationally to combat this global problem.**\n",
